props.name: prompt
props.description: The quality we're rating on (Ex: Overall, has meaningful impact)

props.name: description
props.description: Additional description (shown below the rating bars)

props.name: votes
props.description: Container for votes of kiva, user, and avergage community vetter

props.name: avgs

CVNumberLine.name: CVNumberLine
CVNumberLine.description: Creates a number line with a value enclose in a circle

props.name: id
props.description: HTML element id (required to make sure Number lines don't conflict)

props.name: title
props.description: Title of this number line (what we're measuring)

props.name: start
props.description: Staring value of the number line (1 on a scale of 1 to 10)

props.name: scale
props.description: Highest number on the number line (10 on a scale of 1 to 10)

props.name: color
props.description: Color to render the line (and associated text)

EvaluationPage.name: EvaluationPage
EvaluationPage.description:
This page compares the user's rating of an organization and Kiva's
This is the last page where we "debrief" the user after they test rating an org

params.name: loanApproved
params.description: Whether or not Kiva approved this loan

ReviewPage.name: ReviewPage
ReviewPage.description: Shows all the details of the organization that the user can use to help them vet. For example, it shows amount requested, location, documentation from the startup, etc.

Loan.name: Loan
Loan.description:
Loan is meant to be shared between server and client side code
 It's properties match those in the GraphQL scheme (insofar as possible)
It's constructor takes no arguments. All properties must be set with the
 results of a GraphQL API call/MongoDB call.
However: Note that contained objects, like 'geocode' or 'image' that have
 their own types in the GraphQL API do not have their own types here. They
 are simply treated as vanilla JSON objects

classitems.description: Title: Text to be displayed on button
Secondary: If true (or merely defined like <button secondary>), uses the secondary button style (white background, green border, green text)
On Click: Function called when the button is pressed
Background Color: Allows the background color to be overridden. Otherwise, we use the color defined in CVButton.css
Border Radius: Allows the border radius to be overridden (X pixels). Otherwise, we use the radius defined in CVButton.css
Font Size: Allows the font size to be overridden (X pixels). Otherwise, we use the size defined in CVButton.css
Horizontal Padding: Allows the horizontal padding of the text to be overridden. Otherwise, there is no explicit padding define (except a min-width of 320px)

                                 Kiva CrowdVet
 
                          Component: CVSegmentedControl
 
      Shows a segmented control. This component can be configured in two ways
          The default option presents one tab as "active" (slightly darker than the others)   
          When the progressMode prop is true, options allow for before-active, active, and after-active colors
            (Tabs the user has already done are light green, the current is dark green, the following are white)
 
 State:
  int index: The index of the currently active tab
  
 Props: 
  int index? = The currently active tab. If none, assumes 0 value
  string[] labels = 
  string[] colors = [active color, inactive/before-active color, (if applicable) after-active color]
  bool progressMode? = Optionally enables the three color progress control

Presents a gray info card/chip with bright green info text inside
  1. string? header: an optional top title
  2. string primary: the primary text/statistic we're showing (in big green)
  3. string? footer: an optional bottom subtitle
Dynamically constructs a CVStatCard using the provided props

Presents a custom table using the provided props:
  1. string? title: an optional table title
  2. string[] cols: an array of column names
  3. data[][] data: a 2d array of data for each row (treat the first index of each row as the row's title)
  3. string? footer: an optional table footer
Dynamically constructs a table using the provided props
Title?: Optionally show a table title
Cols: The names of the columns (as an array)

Rows: The data we'll draw into each row (as a 2d array). 
We treat the first element of each row as that row's title
For example, [['apple', 'red', '2.3oz'],['lemon','yellow','1.2oz']]
Footer?: Optionally show some footer text

Temple Hack4Impact
                                 Kiva CrowdVet
 
                            Page: Default Page Temp
 
 
     ALL CONTENT MUST BE EMBEDDED WITHIN A <Page> tag
     This is based off of Jake's template in index.html
 
      This allows us to put the page content that we each
      program (found in ./pages/) and a header comoponent
      (either the user's profile or the "Dance Peace" style
      header) into the page.
 
      This will avoid the case where we each have to add the HTML
      for the default template to our pages.
 
 State:
  
 
 Page Layout:
Binds matching properties in your input object to the Loan object, making sure that no new top-level properties are created.
classitems.name: bind

params.name: object
params.description: object whose properties can be found in Loan.js. We will deep update this Loan object witht the values in your object. Perhaps this object is the result of a call to the GraphQL/MongoDB api?

throws.description: If your input object has a top-level property that doesn't exist in the Loan object (you are discouraged from created new properties)

classitems.description: Internal method which creates a copy of the Loan object's properties/values
classitems.name: toObject

return.description: A copy of this Loan object (excluding methods, etc)

classitems.description: Copies key/value pairs from this object into their matching variable in this Loan object
